                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>MR. WALFORD conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18220220-131-person1279">
                  GEORGE 
                  ELLIS
               <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1279" type="surname" value="ELLIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1279" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1279" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a patrol. On the 15th of February, between seven and eight o'clock at night, I stopped the prisoner at Mile-end-road, and asked what was in his basket - he gave no answer - I took him to a light, and found the brass in it. He said he brought it from his lodgings at Stratford - I found he did lodge there, opposite opposite Hart's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18220220-131-person1280">
                  FRANCIS 
                  OLIVER
               <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1280" type="surname" value="OLIVER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1280" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1280" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Miller, in Mr. 
               <persName id="t18220220-131-person1281">
                  George 
                  Hart
               <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1281" type="surname" value="Hart"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1281" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220220-131-person1281" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's service; the prisoner was also in his employ till the Saturday before he was taken. I know the brass to be my master's by a notch in it. I have seen it about the mill for two or three years.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BRODRICK. Q. It has been throwing about the place. - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18220220-131-verdict712" type="verdictDescription">
